To illustrate future changes, we compare the 20-year mean of physical and biological variables between the two periods (i.e., period 1 and period 2) (Fig. 2). The temperature increase in the upper 100 m occurs over the entire CCS, although there is strong spatial variability. For example, large increases are found in the northwestern corner of the domain, over 1000 km offshore from the Oregon coast, and relatively small increases are found close to the coast of Baja California (Fig. 2a). Buoyancy frequency, defined as \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
